ders with Suzuki’s life and career and analyzes the book’s reception in light of contemporary criticism, especially by scholars of Japanese Buddhism. Zen and Japanese Culture is a valuable source for those wishing to understand Zen in the context of Japanese life and art, and remains one of the leading works on the subject.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPhilosophy, Japanese. 0aZen BuddhismzJapan. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Zen.2bisacsh  aAdult.  aAestheticism.  aAlan Watts.  aAldous Huxley.  aAmerican philosophy.  aAmericans.  aAn Introduction to Zen Buddhism.  aArnold Toynbee.  aBibliography.  aBodhidharma.  aBollingen Foundation.  aBook review.  aBuddhism in Japan.  aBuddhism.  aBuddhist Library (Singapore).  aBuddhist modernism.  aBuddhist philosophy.  aBuddhist texts.  aCarl Jung.  aCharles Richard Crane.  aChristmas Humphreys.  aClaremont Colleges.  aConfucianism.  aContinental philosophy.  aCultural critic.  aCultural heritage.  aCultural relations.  aCulture of Japan.  aEmanuel Swedenborg.  aEmiko Ohnuki-Tierney.  aEnvironmental degradation.  aEranos.  aExploration.  aFriedrich Schleiermacher.  aGary Snyder.  aGautama Buddha.  aGenre.  aGershom Scholem.  aHagakure.  aHandbook.  aHeinrich Dumoulin.  aHenry Corbin.  aHuineng.  aJ. (newspaper).  aJack Kerouac.  aJapanese aesthetics.  aJapanese architecture.  aJapanese art.  aJapanese militarism.  aKaren Horney.  aLecture.  aLiterature.  aMahayana.  aMax Knoll.  aMircea Eliade.  aModernity.  aMr.  aMushin (mental state).  aNatural environment.  aNew Generation (Malayalam film movement).  aNobility.  aNovelist.  aPamphlet.  aPaperback.  aPaul Carus.  aPerennial philosophy.  aPhilip Whalen.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy.  aPhysicist.  